{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630975"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:21:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17336"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17336"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.05,0.13,0.05,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70303"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10026"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55767"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6893"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23539"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23600"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70303"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with haematemesis. She has a history of chronic alcohol use and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her vital signs are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulse rate: 110/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood pressure: 95/60 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory rate: 22/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpO2: 98% on room air\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETemperature: 36.5\u00b0C\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer abdomen is soft but tender in the epigastrium. Upper endoscopy shows a bleeding gastric ulcer in the fundus of the stomach (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries is most likely to be the primary source of blood supply to this region?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left gastric artery","Right gastroepiploic artery","Right gastric artery","Left gastroepiploic artery","Short gastric arteries"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundus of the stomach receives its primary blood supply from the \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort gastric arteries\u003C/strong\u003E, which branch from the splenic artery. These vessels are particularly relevant in this case of fundal gastric varices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther arteries supplying the stomach have different distributions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastric artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the superior portion of the lesser curvature, originating directly from the coeliac trunk\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright gastric artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the inferior portion of the lesser curvature, originating from the hepatic artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastroepiploic artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the superior portion of the greater curvature, originating from the splenic artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eright gastroepiploic artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the inferior portion of the greater curvature, originating from the gastroduodenal artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese vessels form extensive anastomotic networks along both the greater and lesser curvatures of the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The short gastric arteries arise from the splenic artery and supply the fundus of the stomach.","The left gastric artery is a direct branch of the coeliac trunk and supplies the superior half of the lesser curvature of the stomach.","The right gastroepiploic artery arises from the gastroduodenal artery and supplies the inferior part of the greater curvature of the stomach."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55767"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17336"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21314"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21314"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xeyX3w6SfMHfk6HugxBnJEd4RkWfzs.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xeyX3w6SfMHfk6HugxBnJEd4RkWfzs.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":535,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55767"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T14:42:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T14:42:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10026"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70303"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attribut